messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
Yeah, we need somebody at the Center Middle School gym.
What's going on there?
We have an athlete who is on the court, moaning on his back. Could be dehydrated, could be having a seizure.
This is at the high school?
No, this is at the middle school.
And it's called the Center Middle School?
Yes.
Do you know the actual address there, sir?
Hey, does anybody know the address here? 700 East 4th Street.
And this is in the gym?
Yes.
And your name?
Greg Hall.
Okay, so tell me exactly what happened.
We had basketball tryouts today, the first day of tryouts, and at the end of practice, he just collapsed on the ground.
Okay, and are you with him now?
They're on the way, right? Yeah. They're on the way, sir.
Are you with the patient now?
Yes.
How old is he?
He is 13 or 14 years old.
Is he awake?
They're on their way here, guys. He's awake, but barely.
Is he breathing?
Is he breathing, Mike? Very erratic.
Okay. And so he just collapsed, like he fainted almost?
Almost, yeah.
Is he breathing completely normal?
I'm sorry, sir. Is he breathing completely normal? No, he is not. His eyes are rolled back a bit.
Okay. Is he changing color?
Yes. Mike, what do you say? He's changing color. Flip. Yeah.
What color?
They're starting to go blue a little bit.
Does he have a history of heart problems that you're aware of?
We don't know. Nobody's aware of heart problems with this guy, right? No. He's a first-year player. He should have passed a physical, too.
Okay. Is there a defibrillator on site and ready to use?
Yes, there is a defibrillator.
Okay. Have someone grab that in case we need it later. Now, you said he is not alert. Is he conscious or unconscious?
What do you say, is he conscious or unconscious, Mike? He's semi-conscious.
Okay. We're getting no movement. What I want you to do is get him flat on his back, nothing under his head.
Okay. Yeah, that's where he's at now.
Okay. I want you to kneel next to him, look in his mouth. Is there any food or vomit?
Look in his mouth. Is there food or vomit? There's nothing. No, there isn't.
Is he breathing?
No. He has stopped breathing.
Okay. Place your hand on his forehead. Your other hand under his neck, then tilt his head back.
Yep, it's back.
Now I want you to put your ear next to his mouth. Can you feel or hear any breathing?
No.
Okay. I'm going to tell you how to give mouth to mouth.
Okay, mouth to mouth. Go ahead.
If you're trained in CPR, you can certainly perform CPR.
Okay. Yep, we're doing it now.
Okay, so you're doing that now?
Yep, we're doing it now.
Do you have the defibrillator?
Yes.
Okay, I want you to put the defibrillator on the floor next to his head, on the side closest to you.
Okay.
Now you want to remove his shirt.
Now we have it pulled up. Do we need to remove it or can we just pull it up?
As long as you've got his bare chest.
Okay. We've got fluid coming out of his mouth. We turned him to the side.
Clean out his mouth.
Is there someone there that can open the AED and get it set up?
Yes, we have three people here.
Do you have paramedics there now?
No, not yet.
Okay.
Are the pads already plugged into the machine, sir?
No.
Okay, someone needs to install the pads, plug the pads in. There should be instructions as part of the machine.
Okay. We're working on it. Can somebody help me out with the pads, you guys? We got CPR going on. We need to get the pads and stuff.
The engine is getting really close.
What do they need out of here to use?
The pads should usually be in a flat foil or plastic package.
Can't see the pads? Yeah, if they're not plugged in, they're usually in a foil package or some sort of plastic package.
It could be underneath the unit itself.
I'm doing my best. I am. Do you find them? We're looking. We've got tons of fluid coming out.
Tilt his head to the side and clean out the fluid in his mouth.
We're doing that as much as we can.
You got the ETA on these guys?
The engine is pulling up now, but you need to keep working on him.
Here they are, guys. Here they are.
Okay, they're here now.
Okay, I'll let you go. Thank you.
